.TH MIDITEXT 1 2026-07-09 "Linux" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
miditext \- convert a MIDI 1.0 standard file to textmidi language
.SH SYNOPSIS
.SY miditext
.OP OPTION
.OP \-\-midi INPUT
.OP \-\-textmidi OUTPUT
.YS

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B miditext
Converts a text file description of a MIDI file to textmidi language
.B miditext 
is fully documented in a PDF file miditext.pdf.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-\-midi\  input_file
The input file; a standard MIDI 1.0 file.
.
.
.TP
.BI \-\-textmidi\  output_file
The output file; a text file in textmidi language.
.
.
.TP
.BI \-\-dotted_rhythms\  true|false
If true and lazy is selected, then dotted rhythms are written for the appropriate rhythms.
If false and lazy is selected, then rhythms are written without using dots.
.
.
.TP
.BI \-\-rhythmexpression\  rational|simplecontinuedfraction
The output file; a text file in textmidi language.
.
.
.TP
.BI \-\-dynamics_configuration\  {dynamics_file}
Specify the optional file of dynamic values for the lazy mode dynamics symbols, for example, mf, forte, fff etc.
The format of the file is of symbols with equal signs and MIDI velocity values for each symbol.
The symbols may be in any order.  It is not necessary to set all of the available symbols.
If a symbol does not appear, then a default value is used.
Format:
.nf
ppppp=5
pppp=10
ppp=25
pp=40
p=50
mp=62
mf=75
forte=90
ff=110
fff=120
ffff=127
fffff=127
.fi
.
.
.TP
.BI \-\-quantize\  \(aqnumerator/denominator\(aq
A musical rhythm ratio to which to quantize the durations.  
Quotes are typically needed in command shells.
For example "1/16" would quantize to a sixteenth note.
.
.
.TP
.B \-\-lazy
Generate output in textmidi "lazy" mode, an abbreviated
representation that represents musical notes rather than
note-on and note-off pairs.
.
.
.TP
.B \-\-answer
Ask to verify to overwrite the output file if the output file exists.
.
.
.TP
.B \-\-version
Print the version of the program.
.
.
.TP
.B \-\-verbose
Print additional information during processing.
.
.
.TP
.B \-\-help
Print the command line options.
.
.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B miditext
always returns an EXIT_SUCCESS.
